Sure! In LATEX, a table of contents can be generated automatically using a combination of commands. Here is an example of how this can be done:

1. Begin your document with the document class command. For example, if you are using the article class, your document would begin with:
\documentclass{article}

2. Then, use the \tableofcontents command to generate the table of contents. This command should be placed where you want the table of contents to appear in your document.

3. Use the \section{} command to divide your document into sections. The text inside the brackets will be the title of the section and will also appear in the table of contents.

Here's an example of a simple LATEX document with a table of contents:

\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction to the document.

\section{Main Body}
This is the main body of the document.

\subsection{Subsection 1}
This is a subsection within the main body.

\subsection{Subsection 2}
This is another subsection within the main body.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion of the document.

\end{document}

When this document is compiled, a table of contents will be generated at the beginning of the document, listing the sections and subsections. The table of contents will also include page numbers, so you can easily navigate to different sections of the document.

